    "# 2025-09-22 Gram-Schmidt\n",
    "\n",
    "* Revisit projections, rotations, and reflections\n",
    "\n",
    "* Constructing orthogonal bases\n",
    "\n",
    "* QR factorization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "3c5d83a7-2925-456d-b8c9-2e056a00403a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "vander (generic function with 2 methods)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "using LinearAlgebra\n",
    "using Plots\n",
    "using Polynomials\n",
    "default(lw=4, ms=5, legendfontsize=12, xtickfontsize=12, ytickfontsize=12)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Here's our Vandermonde matrix again\n",
    "function vander(x, k=nothing)\n",
    "    if isnothing(k)\n",
    "        k = length(x)\n",
    "    end\n",
    "    m = length(x)\n",
    "    V = ones(m, k)\n",
    "    for j in 2:k\n",
    "        V[:, j] = V[:, j-1] .* x\n",
    "    end\n",
    "    V\n",
    "end"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "x = LinRange(-1, 1, 50)\n",
    "A = vander(x, 4)\n",
    "M = A * [.5 0 0 0;  # 0.5\n",
    "         0  1 0 0;  # x\n",
    "         0  0 1 0]' # x^2\n",
    "\n",
    "scatter(x, M, label=[\"\\$0.5\\$\" \"\\$x\\$\" \"\\$x^2\\$\"])\n",
    "plot!(x, 0*x, label=:none, color=:black)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7fc4dd74-a2d3-439f-ae85-7a07a99bc0bd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Which inner products will be zero?\n",
    "\n",
    "Which functions are even and odd?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "557f17fb-cf68-4d7f-b6aa-6eb8b4c3b74d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Pairwise inner product\n",
    "\n",
    "The pairwise inner products between two sets of vectors can be expressed by collecting the sets as columns in matrices and writing $A = X^T Y$, where $A_{i, j} = x_i^T y_j$.\n",
    "It follows from this definition that\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ \\left( X^T Y \\right)^T = Y^T X $$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "8564dd60-ed7f-4da8-905d-962ce8981ae4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "(M' * M)' == M' * M = true\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "33 Matrix{Float64}:\n",
       " 12.5          -1.11022e-15   8.67347\n",

       "  8.67347      -2.22045e-16  10.8272"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's verify this\n",
    "@show (M' * M)' == M' * M\n",
    "M' * M"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e090bf2-3a90-41c1-9bbe-f4f61d409dc5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Orthogonal matrices\n",
    "\n",
    "If $x^T y = 0$, then we say $x$ and $y$ are **orthogonal** (or $x$ is orthogonal to $y$).\n",
    "\n",
    "A vector is said to be **normalized** if $\\left\\lvert \\left\\lvert x \\right\\rvert \\right\\rvert = 1$.\n",
    "\n",
    "If $x$ is orthogonal to $y$ and $\\left\\lvert \\left\\lvert x \\right\\rvert \\right\\rvert = \\left\\lvert \\left\\lvert y \\right\\rvert \\right\\rvert = 1$, then we say $x$ and $y$ are **orthogonal**.\n",
    "\n",
    "A square matrix with orthonormal columns is said to be an **orthogonal matrix**.\n",
    "\n",
    "We typically use $Q$ or $U$ and $V$ for matrices that are know/constructed to be orogonal.\n",
    "Orthogonal matrices are always full rank - the columns are linearly independent.\n",
    "The inverse of a orthogonal matrix is its transpose.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ Q^T Q = Q Q^T = I $$\n",
    "\n",
    "Orthogonal matrices are a powerful building block for robust numerical algorithms."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a9e0d0ce-cf1a-4cd0-a56b-e0886ccc19d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we're given some vectors and want to find an  orthogonal basis for their span.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ A = \\begin{split} \\Bigg[ a_1 \\Bigg| a_2 \\Bigg] = \\Bigg[ q_1 \\Bigg| q_2 \\Bigg] \\begin{bmatrix} r_{11} & r_{12} \\\\ 0 & r_{22} \\end{bmatrix} \\end{split} = Q R$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "700ea717-5276-44e8-9410-2fae8af20b07",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## A naive Gram-Schmidt algorithm"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "c53d6b48-d3fb-4a31-9913-8eb50d68f2dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "gram_schmidt_naive (generic function with 1 method)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's form Q and R by making each column orthonormal to all previous columns\n",
    "function gram_schmidt_naive(A)\n",
    "    m, n = size(A)\n",
    "    Q = zeros(m, n) # Orthonormal basis\n",
    "    R = zeros(n, n) # Upper triangular\n",
    "    for j in 1:n\n",
    "        v = A[:, j] # current column to normalize\n",
    "        for k in 1:j-1\n",
    "            # We do a projection against the previous\n",
    "            #  columns of Q. Why?\n",
    "            r  = Q[:, k]' * v \n",
    "            v -= Q[:, k] * r\n",
    "            R[k, j] = r # What is this factor?\n",
    "        end\n",
    "        # normalize and store our final v\n",
    "        R[j, j] = norm(v)\n",
    "        Q[:, j] = v / R[j, j]\n",
    "    end\n",
    "    Q, R\n",
    "end"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "c7d63f22-63fe-4c70-829b-c151f0751414",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "norm(Q' * Q - I) = 1.0245877047652434e-15\n",
      "norm(Q * R - A) = 4.3681794554507014e-16\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's try it with the Vandermonde matrix\n",
    "A = vander(x, 4)\n",
    "Q, R = gram_schmidt_naive(A)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Check this is valid\n",
    "@show norm(Q' * Q - I)\n",
    "@show norm(Q * R - A);"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Let's look at 6 orthonormal polynomials\n",
    "x = LinRange(-1, 1, 50)\n",
    "A = vander(x, 6)\n",
    "Q, R = gram_schmidt_naive(A)\n",
    "plot(x, Q, legend=:none)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "14684df8-54c1-4aa3-a4e7-924799a2da91",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What happen if we use more than $50$ values of $x$?\n",
    "Is there a continuous limit?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "39258c1d-62c3-4e78-b81c-b5af44b172fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Theorem\n",
    "\n",
    "Every full-rank $m \\times n$ matrix ($m \\geq n$) has a unique reduced $QR$ factorization with $R_{j, j} > 0$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The algorithm we're using generates this matrix due to the line:\n",
    "\n",
    "```julia\n",
    "        R[j,j] = norm(v)\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d4a486f8-0414-43f1-8625-998b712db952",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Solving equations with $QR$\n",
    "\n",
    "If $A x = b$, then $R x = Q^T b$."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Let's fit a polynomial to these points\n",
    "x1 = [-0.9, 0.1, 0.5, 0.8]\n",
    "y1 = [1, 2.4, -0.2, 1.3]\n",
    "scatter(x1, y1, label=\"data\")\n",
    "\n",
    "Q, R = gram_schmidt_naive(vander(x1, 4))\n",
    "p = R \\ (Q' * y1) # Using \\ to solve R^-1, easy for upper triangular\n",
    "@show p\n",
    "plot!(x, vander(x, 4) * p, label=\"\\$R^{-1}Q^Tb\\$\")"
   ]
  },

    "m = 20\n",
    "x = LinRange(-1, 1, m)\n",

   "source": [
    "## A variant with more parallelism\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ q_2 q_2^T \\left( q_1 q_1^T v \\right) = q_2 \\left( q_2^T q_1 \\right) q_1^T v = 0 $$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "527936f2-3a92-4ce2-9fac-af2b9769794f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "gram_schmidt_classical (generic function with 1 method)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 11,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's form Q and R by making each column orthonormal to all previous columns\n",
    "function gram_schmidt_classical(A)\n",
    "    m, n = size(A)\n",
    "    # Same setup as our niave version\n",
    "    Q = zeros(m, n)\n",
    "    R = zeros(n, n)\n",
    "    for j in 1:n\n",
    "        v = A[: ,j]\n",
    "        R[1:j-1, j] = Q[:, 1:j-1]' * v\n",
    "        v -= Q[:, 1:j-1] * R[1:j-1, j]\n",
    "        R[j, j] = norm(v)\n",
    "        Q[:, j] = v / norm(v)\n",
    "    end\n",
    "    Q, R\n",
    "end"
   ]
  },
